{"title_page": "21c Museum Hotels", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| name = 21c Museum Hotels\n| founded = {{Start date and age|2006}}\n| founders = {{Unbulleted list|Laura Lee Brown|Steve Wilson}}\n| hq_location_city = [[Louisville, Kentucky]]\n| hq_location_country = United States\n| num_locations = 8 hotels (+ 2 more under development)\n| area_served = [[United States]]\n| industry = Hotel\n| parent = [[AccorHotels]]\n| website = http://www.21cmuseumhotels.com/\n}}\n\n'''21c Museum Hotels''' is a [[Louisville, Kentucky|Louisville]]-based combination [[Contemporary art|contemporary art museum]] and [[boutique hotel]] chain. As of 2018, it has been acquired by [[AccorHotels]] and manages nine properties in [[Louisville, Kentucky]]; [[Lexington, Kentucky]]; [[Cincinnati, Ohio]]; [[Chicago, Illinois]], [[Bentonville, Arkansas]], [[Durham, North Carolina]], [[Oklahoma City, OK]], [[Kansas City, MO]] and [[Nashville, Tennessee]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.21cmuseumhotels.com/durham/|title=21c Museum Hotel Durham - Downtown Durham Luxury Hotel|author=21c Museum Hotels|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n21c Museum Hotel was voted among the Top 10 Hotels in the World in the ''[[Cond\u00e9 Nast Traveler]]'' Readers' Choice Awards in 2009, 2010 and 2011.<ref>\"2009 Readers' Choice Awards,\" ''Conde Nast Traveler'', October 2009.  http://www.concierge.com/ideas/luxury/tours/501143?page=5 {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928001255/http://www.concierge.com/ideas/luxury/tours/501143?page=5 |date=2011-09-28 }}</ref> It was also voted as the No. 1 Hotel in the South in the 2012 ''[[Cond\u00e9 Nast Traveler]]'' Readers' Choice Awards.\n[[Hotel Metropole (Cincinnati, Ohio)|21c Museum Hotel Cincinnati]] was named the top hotel in America in 2013 by Conde Nast Traveler's annual reader survey, and 11th in the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/cincinnati/news/2013/04/18/21c-museum-hotel-cincinnati-named-to.html|title=21c Museum Hotel Cincinnati named to Cond\u00e9 Nast Traveler's Hot List|last=Demeropolis|first=Tom|date=2013-04-18|website=www.bizjournals.com|access-date=2017-09-07}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n21c Museum Hotel was launched in 2006 by philanthropists and art collectors Laura Lee Brown and Steve Wilson. The pair had seen farmland and rural landscapes fall to development while the historic buildings of Louisville's downtown sat vacant. They created 21c in Louisville's downtown arts and theater district to support both [[urban renewal]] and regional agriculture, and have developed partnerships with local growers to supply produce and ingredients for the Proof on Main restaurant and bar.\n\nFollowing the success of the Louisville location, additional 21c locations were put into motion, with 7 currently in operation and more in the planning or construction stages.\n\nIn July 2018, 21C Museum Hotels was acquired by the French Hotel Group [[AccorHotels]] for a sum of $51 Million. Founders Brown and Wilson maintain a 15% stake and continue to be involved with the company.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/louisville/news/2018/07/31/21c-museum-hotels-sold-to-international-hotel.html|title=21c Museum Hotels to be sold to international hotel chain|last=Mann|first=David|date=July 31, 2018|website=BizJournals.com|access-date=September 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==21c Museum==\n\n'''21c Museum''' is North America's only museum dedicated to collecting and exhibiting contemporary art of the 21st century. The museum is open free of charge 24 hours a day, seven days a week. More than twenty special exhibitions and installations have been organized by the 21c Museum since its opening in 2006.\n\nRecent exhibitions include: \"Creating Identity: Portraiture Today;\" \"All's Fair in Art and War: Envisioning Conflict;\" \"Tangled Up In You: Connecting, Coexisting, and Conceiving Identity,\" and \"Hybridity: The Evolution of Species and Spaces in 21st-Century Art.\"  21c Museum has presented projects by [[Mikhail Baryshnikov]] and [[John Waters (filmmaker)|John Waters]], as well as traveling exhibitions including Marc Swanson: Beginning to See the Light, organized by the Santa Barbara Contemporary Arts Forum, and Constant World: the Work of Jennifer and Kevin McCoy, organized by Beall Center for Art and Technology, University of California, Irvine.\n\n===Artworks===\n\nThe 21c Museum features permanent installations and special exhibitions of works by artists, including [[Bill Viola]], [[Tony Oursler]], [[Andres Serrano]], [[Sam Taylor-Wood]], [[David Levinthal]], [[Yyinka Shonibare]], [[Judy Fox]], [[Chuck Close]], [[Alfredo Jaar]], [[David Herbert (artist)|David Herbert]], [[Daan Roosegaarde]], [[Anastasia Schipani]], [[Kara Walker]] and [[Serkan \u00d6zkaya]] (''[[David (inspired by Michelangelo)|David]]'').\n\nThe museum also displays a number of original site-specific commissions, including:\n*''Untitled'' (2006) by [[Werner Reiterer]], the artist's first permanent public sculpture in the U.S.\n*''In the Absence of Voyeurism 6 & 7'' (2000\u20132006) by artist and surgeon Sean Bidic\n*''Cloud Rings'' (2006) by [[MacArthur Fellow]] [[Ned Kahn]]\n*''Red Penguin'' (2005) by Cracking Art Group\n*''Arilated'': The 21c Pip Mobile (2005\u20132007) by Monica Mahoney\n*''Text Rain'' (1999) by [[Camille Utterback]] and Romy Achituv\n*Sculptures from the Satyrs Daughters 1999 series and Figure 2004 series by [[Judy Fox]]\n*''Flow 5.0'' (2013) by [[Daan Roosegaarde]]\n*''Echo'' (2017) by [[Heather Gordon]] and [[Justin Tornow]]\n\n==Locations==\n=== Louisville, Kentucky ===\nThe Louisville location renovated five 19th century [[tobacco]] and [[Bourbon whiskey|bourbon]] warehouse buildings listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] to house the museum, hotel, and its restaurant. It is located within the city's arts and theater district along \"Museum Row,\" which is home to the [[Louisville Slugger Museum]] and Factory, the [[Muhammad Ali Center]], the [[Frazier History Museum]], the [[Kentucky Museum of Art and Craft]], and the [[Kentucky Science Center]]. This location has a restaurant named [https://web.archive.org/web/20091009131148/http://www.proofonmain.com/proof/Default.aspx Proof on Main], which was named one of \"Best New Restaurants 2006\" by ''Esquire'' magazine.<ref>\"Best New Restaurants 2006,\" ''Esquire'', October 2006.  http://www.esquire.com/features/food-drink/ESQ1106BNR_110</ref>  The menu features ingredients from local farms and food purveyors, as well as 50 types of bourbon.<ref>\"America's 50 Most Amazing Wine Experiences,\" ''Food & Wine'', October 2006.  http://www.foodandwine.com/articles/americas-50-most-amazing-wine-experiences</ref> Located outside the establishment stands The Statue of David, a double-size, golden replica of Michelangelo's ''David'', created by Turkish artist, Serkan \u00d6zkaya.<ref>{{cite web |title=David (inspired by Michelangelo) |url=https://www.21cmuseumhotels.com/museum/exhibit/david-inspired-by-michelangelo-2/ |website=21c Museum Hotel |accessdate=10 February 2020}}</ref> Originally a project for the Istanbul Biennial art exhibition, David unfortunately collapsed under his own weight. \u00d6zkaya salvaged and restored the statue and created two more casts, one of which was acquired by 21c Museum Hotels.<ref>{{cite web |title=Golden Statue of David |url=https://www.atlasobscura.com/places/golden-statue-of-david |website=Atlas Obscura |accessdate=10 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe facility was designed by [[Deborah Berke & Partners Architects]], for which they won the [[American Institute of Architects]] Kentucky Honor Award in 2011,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aiaky.org/index.php/calendarj/honor-awards/73-events-and-programs/honor-awards-program/honor-awards-2011/191-honor-awards-2011|publisher=AIA KY|title=Honor Awards|year=2011}}</ref> the AIA NYS Excellence for Historic Preservation/Adaptive Reuse in 2007,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aianys.org/awards/2007_awards.htm |year=2007 |publisher=AIA NYS |title=Design Awards Layout |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120225182419/http://www.aianys.org/awards/2007_awards.htm |archivedate=2012-02-25 }}</ref> and the Best of Year Award for Hospitality Design, Interior Design Magazine, in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.interiordesign.net/article/481328-Best_of_Year_Awards_2006.php |title=Best of Year Awards |year=2006 |work=Interior Design |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120325025839/http://www.interiordesign.net/article/481328-Best_of_Year_Awards_2006.php |archivedate=2012-03-25 }}</ref>\n\n=== Cincinnati, Ohio ===\nThe Cincinnati location involved the complete renovation of the historic [[Hotel Metropole (Cincinnati, Ohio)|Hotel Metropole]], a grand building that's most previous use was [[Section 8 (housing)|section 8]] apartments for low income residents. $48 million was spent on the renovation.\n\n=== Bentonville, Arkansas ===\nThe third location in Bentonville opened in 2013. The museum hotel is a small walk away from the [[Crystal Bridges Museum of American Art]]. The hotel is located on land that was once a corn field outside of the urban center of Bentonville.<ref>\"Waltons back 'arts' hotel,\" Arkansas Times, June 2010, http://www.arktimes.com/ArkansasBlog/archives/2010/06/08/waltons-back-arts-hotel</ref>\n\nThe Bentonville location was named one of the top 15 hotels in the US by [[Travel + Leisure|Travel + Leisure Magazine]] in 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://5newsonline.com/2017/07/28/bentonvilles-21c-museum-hotel-ranks-among-top-in-nation/|title=Bentonville's 21c Museum Hotel Ranks Among Top In Nation|date=2017-07-29|work=Fort Smith/Fayetteville News {{!}} 5newsonline KFSM 5NEWS|access-date=2018-05-27|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n=== Durham, North Carolina ===\nIn March 2015 21c opened its fourth hotel in [[Durham, North Carolina]].<ref>[http://www.newsobserver.com/news/local/community/durham-news/article14569736.html 21c Museum Hotel opens], ''The News & Observer'', March 17, 2015</ref> In 2013 the company bought the historic [[Hill Building]] for $5.25 million. With an investment of $48 million the [[Hill Building]] was renovated and converted into a hotel with 125 rooms.<ref>Barbara De Lollis, [http://travel.usatoday.com/hotels/post/2012/08/21c-museum-hotel-durham-oks-6-million-in-incentives/819552/1 \"Durham, N.C., to get artsy, luxury 21c Museum Hotel\"], ''[[USA Today]]'', August 8, 2012.</ref><ref>Amanda Jones Hoyle, [http://www.bizjournals.com/triangle/news/2013/06/28/construction-starts-on-21c-museum.html \"Construction starts on 21c Museum Hotel in Durham\"], ''[[Triangle Business Journal]]'', June 28, 2013.</ref> The hotel is centrally located in Downtown Durham and is a short walk from the Durham Bulls Stadium, the DPAC and the Carolina Theater.\n\n=== Lexington, Kentucky ===\nIn February 2016 the Lexington hotel opened in the [[Fayette National Bank Building|Fayette National Bank]] (aka First National Bank) building.\n<ref>[https://www.21cmuseumhotels.com/lexington/blog/2016/21c-opens-fifth-property/ 21c opens fifth property], 21c Blog, February 2, 2016</ref><ref>Janet Patton, [http://www.kentucky.com/2013/08/31/2798151/lexingtons-21c-hotel-delayed-to.html \"Lexington's 21c hotel delayed to 2015, but 'definitely not dead'\"], ''[[Lexington Herald-Leader]]'', August 31, 2013.</ref>\n\n=== Oklahoma City, Oklahoma ===\nIn June 2016 21c opened a hotel in [[Oklahoma City, Oklahoma]] in the Fred Jones Assembly Plant built in 1915, where the Ford Model T was assembled.<ref>[https://www.21cmuseumhotels.com/oklahomacity/blog/2016/21c-museum-hotel-opens-oklahoma-city/ 21c Museum hotel opens in Oklahoma City], Press release, June 6, 2016</ref><ref>Steve Lackmeyer, [http://newsok.com/steve-lackmeyer-new-21c-museum-hotel-will-spur-redevelopment-of-other-okc-buildings/article/3945616 \"New 21c Museum Hotel will spur redevelopment of other OKC buildings\"], ''[[The Oklahoman]]'', March 21, 2014.</ref> The hotel has been to Travel + Leisure magazine\u2019s 2017 It List of Best New Hotels Around the World, as one of 44 best new and radically redone hotels and resorts around the world of the past year.<ref>[https://www.21cmuseumhotels.com/oklahomacity/blog/2017/21c-oklahoma-city-named-travel-leisures-list-best-new-hotels-around-world/ 21c Oklahoma City honored by Travel + Leisure], 21c Blog, June 16, 2017</ref>\n\n=== Nashville, Tennessee ===\nIn May 2017 the Nashville hotel opened in the historic Gray & Dudley building in downtown.<ref>[https://www.bizjournals.com/louisville/news/2017/05/11/inside-look-21c-debuts-downtown-nashville-hotel.html Inside look: 21c debuts downtown Nashville hotel], ''Louisville Business First'', May 11, 2017</ref>\n\n=== Kansas City, Missouri ===\nIn July 2018 the group opened their 120 suite and gallery hotel in [[Kansas City, Missouri]] inside the historic [[Savoy Hotel and Grill]] <ref name=\":0\">Kevin Collison, [http://www.kansascity.com/2013/12/02/4664298/savoy-hotel-deal-moving-forward.html \"Savoy Hotel deal moving forward\"], ''[[The Kansas City Star]]'', December 2, 2013.</ref>\n\n=== Further developments ===\nAdditional properties are in active development. A location in [[Des Moines, Iowa]] is expected to complete construction by 2021.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/money/business/new-business/2018/05/08/downtown-fifth-des-moines-high-rise-21-c-museum-hotel-mandelbaum/591472002/|title=Des Moines high-rise project adds boutique hotel, art museum|work=Des Moines Register|access-date=2018-09-22|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe company had been looking to open a hotel in [[Indianapolis]] in the [[Old Indianapolis City Hall|old city hall]], with construction scheduled to begin in 2017, however these plans were scrapped at the end of March 2017 due to problems with financing.<ref>[http://www.indystar.com/story/news/2017/03/27/deal-21c-boutique-hotel-old-city-hall-falls-apart/99699962/ Deal for 21c boutique hotel at old City Hall falls apart], ''Indianapolis Star'', March 27, 2017</ref> 21c Museum Hotels will still be seeking to open a location in the city.\n\n==Restaurants==\nEach 21c location has an onsite restaurant, with many receiving recognition and awards including multiple [[James Beard Foundation Award]] finalists for excellence in cuisine.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nwaonline.com/news/2018/feb/16/bentonville-chef-nominated-for-james-be/|title=Bentonville chef nominated for James Beard award|work=NWADG.com|access-date=2018-05-27|language=en}}</ref>\n\nEach restaurant reflects the local flavor and cuisine of its home city. The current lineup includes:\n\n* The Hive - Bentonville\n* Metropole - Cincinnati\n* Counting House - Durham\n* Lockbox - Lexington\n* Proof on Main - Louisville\n* Gray & Dudley - Nashville\n* Mary Eddy's - Oklahoma City\n* The Savoy - Kansas City\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.21cmuseumhotels.com/}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Hotel chains in the United States]]\n[[Category:Luxury brands]]\n[[Category:2006 establishments in Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Hotels established in 2006]]\n[[Category:Hotels in Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Hotels in Ohio]]\n[[Category:Hotels in Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Louisville, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Art museums established in 2006]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Louisville, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Boutique resort chains]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 2006]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n| name = 21c Museum Hotels\n| founded = {{Start date and age|2006}}\n| founders = {{Unbulleted list|Laura Lee Brown|Steve Wilson}}\n| hq_location_city = [[Louisville, Kentucky]]\n| hq_location_country = United States\n| num_locations = 8 hotels (+ 2 more under development)\n| area_served = [[United States]]\n| industry = Hotel\n| parent = [[AccorHotels]]\n| website = http://www.21cmuseumhotels.com/\n}}\n\n'''21c Museum Hotels''' is a [[Louisville, Kentucky|Louisville]]-based combination [[Contemporary art|contemporary art museum]] and [[boutique hotel]] chain. As of 2018, it has been acquired by [[AccorHotels]] and manages nine properties in [[Louisville, Kentucky]]; [[Lexington, Kentucky]]; [[Cincinnati, Ohio]]; [[Chicago, Illinois]], [[Bentonville, Arkansas]], [[Durham, North Carolina]], [[Oklahoma City, OK]], [[Kansas City, MO]] and [[Nashville, Tennessee]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.21cmuseumhotels.com/durham/|title=21c Museum Hotel Durham - Downtown Durham Luxury Hotel|author=21c Museum Hotels|publisher=}}</ref> \n\n21c Museum Hotel was voted among the Top 10 Hotels in the World in the ''[[Cond\u00e9 Nast Traveler]]'' Readers' Choice Awards in 2009, 2010 and 2011.<ref>\"2009 Readers' Choice Awards,\" ''Conde Nast Traveler'', October 2009.  http://www.concierge.com/ideas/luxury/tours/501143?page=5 {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928001255/http://www.concierge.com/ideas/luxury/tours/501143?page=5 |date=2011-09-28 }}</ref> It was also voted as the No. 1 Hotel in the South in the 2012 ''[[Cond\u00e9 Nast Traveler]]'' Readers' Choice Awards.\n[[Hotel Metropole (Cincinnati, Ohio)|21c Museum Hotel Cincinnati]] was named the top hotel in America in 2013 by Conde Nast Traveler's annual reader survey, and 11th in the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/cincinnati/news/2013/04/18/21c-museum-hotel-cincinnati-named-to.html|title=21c Museum Hotel Cincinnati named to Cond\u00e9 Nast Traveler's Hot List|last=Demeropolis|first=Tom|date=2013-04-18|website=www.bizjournals.com|access-date=2017-09-07}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n21c Museum Hotel was launched in 2006 by philanthropists and art collectors Laura Lee Brown and Steve Wilson. The pair had seen farmland and rural landscapes fall to development while the historic buildings of Louisville's downtown sat vacant. They created 21c in Louisville's downtown arts and theater district to support both [[urban renewal]] and regional agriculture, and have developed partnerships with local growers to supply produce and ingredients for the Proof on Main restaurant and bar.\n\nFollowing the success of the Louisville location, additional 21c locations were put into motion, with 7 currently in operation and more in the planning or construction stages.\n\nIn July 2018, 21C Museum Hotels was acquired by the French Hotel Group [[AccorHotels]] for a sum of $51 Million. Founders Brown and Wilson maintain a 15% stake and continue to be involved with the company.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/louisville/news/2018/07/31/21c-museum-hotels-sold-to-international-hotel.html|title=21c Museum Hotels to be sold to international hotel chain|last=Mann|first=David|date=July 31, 2018|website=BizJournals.com|access-date=September 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==21c Museum==\n\n'''21c Museum''' is North America's only museum dedicated to collecting and exhibiting contemporary art of the 21st century. The museum is open free of charge 24 hours a day, seven days a week. More than twenty special exhibitions and installations have been organized by the 21c Museum since its opening in 2006.\n\nRecent exhibitions include: \"Creating Identity: Portraiture Today;\" \"All's Fair in Art and War: Envisioning Conflict;\" \"Tangled Up In You: Connecting, Coexisting, and Conceiving Identity,\" and \"Hybridity: The Evolution of Species and Spaces in 21st-Century Art.\"  21c Museum has presented projects by [[Mikhail Baryshnikov]] and [[John Waters (filmmaker)|John Waters]], as well as traveling exhibitions including Marc Swanson: Beginning to See the Light, organized by the Santa Barbara Contemporary Arts Forum, and Constant World: the Work of Jennifer and Kevin McCoy, organized by Beall Center for Art and Technology, University of California, Irvine.\n\n===Artworks===\n\nThe 21c Museum features permanent installations and special exhibitions of works by artists, including [[Bill Viola]], [[Tony Oursler]], [[Andres Serrano]], [[Sam Taylor-Wood]], [[David Levinthal]], [[Yyinka Shonibare]], [[Judy Fox]], [[Chuck Close]], [[Alfredo Jaar]], [[David Herbert (artist)|David Herbert]], [[Daan Roosegaarde]], [[Anastasia Schipani]], [[Kara Walker]] and [[Serkan \u00d6zkaya]] (''[[David (inspired by Michelangelo)|David]]'').\n\nThe museum also displays a number of original site-specific commissions, including:\n*''Untitled'' (2006) by [[Werner Reiterer]], the artist's first permanent public sculpture in the U.S.\n*''In the Absence of Voyeurism 6 & 7'' (2000\u20132006) by artist and surgeon Sean Bidic\n*''Cloud Rings'' (2006) by [[MacArthur Fellow]] [[Ned Kahn]]\n*''Red Penguin'' (2005) by Cracking Art Group\n*''Arilated'': The 21c Pip Mobile (2005\u20132007) by Monica Mahoney\n*''Text Rain'' (1999) by [[Camille Utterback]] and Romy Achituv\n*Sculptures from the Satyrs Daughters 1999 series and Figure 2004 series by [[Judy Fox]]\n*''Flow 5.0'' (2013) by [[Daan Roosegaarde]]\n*''Echo'' (2017) by [[Heather Gordon]] and [[Justin Tornow]]\n\n==Locations==\n=== Louisville, Kentucky ===\nThe Louisville location renovated five 19th century [[tobacco]] and [[Bourbon whiskey|bourbon]] warehouse buildings listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] to house the museum, hotel, and its restaurant. It is located within the city's arts and theater district along \"Museum Row,\" which is home to the [[Louisville Slugger Museum]] and Factory, the [[Muhammad Ali Center]], the [[Frazier History Museum]], the [[Kentucky Museum of Art and Craft]], and the [[Kentucky Science Center]]. This location has a restaurant named [https://web.archive.org/web/20091009131148/http://www.proofonmain.com/proof/Default.aspx Proof on Main], which was named one of \"Best New Restaurants 2006\" by ''Esquire'' magazine.<ref>\"Best New Restaurants 2006,\" ''Esquire'', October 2006.  http://www.esquire.com/features/food-drink/ESQ1106BNR_110</ref>  The menu features ingredients from local farms and food purveyors, as well as 50 types of bourbon.<ref>\"America's 50 Most Amazing Wine Experiences,\" ''Food & Wine'', October 2006.  http://www.foodandwine.com/articles/americas-50-most-amazing-wine-experiences</ref> Located outside the establishment stands The Statue of David, a double-size, golden replica of Michelangelo's ''David'', created by Turkish artist, Serkan \u00d6zkaya<ref>{{cite web |title=David (inspired by Michelangelo) |url=https://www.21cmuseumhotels.com/museum/exhibit/david-inspired-by-michelangelo-2/ |website=21c Museum Hotel |accessdate=10 February 2020}}</ref>. Originally a project for the Istanbul Biennial art exhibition, David unfortunately collapsed under his own weight. \u00d6zkaya salvaged and restored the statue and created two more casts, one of which was acquired by 21c Museum Hotels.<ref>{{cite web |title=Golden Statue of David |url=https://www.atlasobscura.com/places/golden-statue-of-david |website=Atlas Obscura |accessdate=10 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe facility was designed by [[Deborah Berke & Partners Architects]], for which they won the [[American Institute of Architects]] Kentucky Honor Award in 2011,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aiaky.org/index.php/calendarj/honor-awards/73-events-and-programs/honor-awards-program/honor-awards-2011/191-honor-awards-2011|publisher=AIA KY|title=Honor Awards|year=2011}}</ref> the AIA NYS Excellence for Historic Preservation/Adaptive Reuse in 2007,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aianys.org/awards/2007_awards.htm |year=2007 |publisher=AIA NYS |title=Design Awards Layout |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120225182419/http://www.aianys.org/awards/2007_awards.htm |archivedate=2012-02-25 }}</ref> and the Best of Year Award for Hospitality Design, Interior Design Magazine, in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.interiordesign.net/article/481328-Best_of_Year_Awards_2006.php |title=Best of Year Awards |year=2006 |work=Interior Design |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120325025839/http://www.interiordesign.net/article/481328-Best_of_Year_Awards_2006.php |archivedate=2012-03-25 }}</ref>\n\n=== Cincinnati, Ohio ===\nThe Cincinnati location involved the complete renovation of the historic [[Hotel Metropole (Cincinnati, Ohio)|Hotel Metropole]], a grand building that's most previous use was [[Section 8 (housing)|section 8]] apartments for low income residents. $48 million was spent on the renovation.\n\n=== Bentonville, Arkansas ===\nThe third location in Bentonville opened in 2013. The museum hotel is a small walk away from the [[Crystal Bridges Museum of American Art]]. The hotel is located on land that was once a corn field outside of the urban center of Bentonville.<ref>\"Waltons back 'arts' hotel,\" Arkansas Times, June 2010, http://www.arktimes.com/ArkansasBlog/archives/2010/06/08/waltons-back-arts-hotel</ref> \n\nThe Bentonville location was named one of the top 15 hotels in the US by [[Travel + Leisure|Travel + Leisure Magazine]] in 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://5newsonline.com/2017/07/28/bentonvilles-21c-museum-hotel-ranks-among-top-in-nation/|title=Bentonville's 21c Museum Hotel Ranks Among Top In Nation|date=2017-07-29|work=Fort Smith/Fayetteville News {{!}} 5newsonline KFSM 5NEWS|access-date=2018-05-27|language=en-US}}</ref> \n\n=== Durham, North Carolina ===\nIn March 2015 21c opened its fourth hotel in [[Durham, North Carolina]].<ref>[http://www.newsobserver.com/news/local/community/durham-news/article14569736.html 21c Museum Hotel opens], ''The News & Observer'', March 17, 2015</ref> In 2013 the company bought the historic [[Hill Building]] for $5.25 million. With an investment of $48 million the [[Hill Building]] was renovated and converted into a hotel with 125 rooms.<ref>Barbara De Lollis, [http://travel.usatoday.com/hotels/post/2012/08/21c-museum-hotel-durham-oks-6-million-in-incentives/819552/1 \"Durham, N.C., to get artsy, luxury 21c Museum Hotel\"], ''[[USA Today]]'', August 8, 2012.</ref><ref>Amanda Jones Hoyle, [http://www.bizjournals.com/triangle/news/2013/06/28/construction-starts-on-21c-museum.html \"Construction starts on 21c Museum Hotel in Durham\"], ''[[Triangle Business Journal]]'', June 28, 2013.</ref> The hotel is centrally located in Downtown Durham and is a short walk from the Durham Bulls Stadium, the DPAC and the Carolina Theater.\n\n=== Lexington, Kentucky ===\nIn February 2016 the Lexington hotel opened in the [[Fayette National Bank Building|Fayette National Bank]] (aka First National Bank) building.\n<ref>[https://www.21cmuseumhotels.com/lexington/blog/2016/21c-opens-fifth-property/ 21c opens fifth property], 21c Blog, February 2, 2016</ref><ref>Janet Patton, [http://www.kentucky.com/2013/08/31/2798151/lexingtons-21c-hotel-delayed-to.html \"Lexington's 21c hotel delayed to 2015, but 'definitely not dead'\"], ''[[Lexington Herald-Leader]]'', August 31, 2013.</ref> \n\n=== Oklahoma City, Oklahoma ===\nIn June 2016 21c opened a hotel in [[Oklahoma City, Oklahoma]] in the Fred Jones Assembly Plant built in 1915, where the Ford Model T was assembled.<ref>[https://www.21cmuseumhotels.com/oklahomacity/blog/2016/21c-museum-hotel-opens-oklahoma-city/ 21c Museum hotel opens in Oklahoma City], Press release, June 6, 2016</ref><ref>Steve Lackmeyer, [http://newsok.com/steve-lackmeyer-new-21c-museum-hotel-will-spur-redevelopment-of-other-okc-buildings/article/3945616 \"New 21c Museum Hotel will spur redevelopment of other OKC buildings\"], ''[[The Oklahoman]]'', March 21, 2014.</ref> The hotel has been to Travel + Leisure magazine\u2019s 2017 It List of Best New Hotels Around the World, as one of 44 best new and radically redone hotels and resorts around the world of the past year.<ref>[https://www.21cmuseumhotels.com/oklahomacity/blog/2017/21c-oklahoma-city-named-travel-leisures-list-best-new-hotels-around-world/ 21c Oklahoma City honored by Travel + Leisure], 21c Blog, June 16, 2017</ref>\n\n=== Nashville, Tennessee ===\nIn May 2017 the Nashville hotel opened in the historic Gray & Dudley building in downtown.<ref>[https://www.bizjournals.com/louisville/news/2017/05/11/inside-look-21c-debuts-downtown-nashville-hotel.html Inside look: 21c debuts downtown Nashville hotel], ''Louisville Business First'', May 11, 2017</ref>\n\n=== Kansas City, Missouri ===\nIn July 2018 the group opened their 120 suite and gallery hotel in [[Kansas City, Missouri]] inside the historic [[Savoy Hotel and Grill]] <ref name=\":0\">Kevin Collison, [http://www.kansascity.com/2013/12/02/4664298/savoy-hotel-deal-moving-forward.html \"Savoy Hotel deal moving forward\"], ''[[The Kansas City Star]]'', December 2, 2013.</ref>\n\n=== Further developments ===\nAdditional properties are in active development. A location in [[Des Moines, Iowa]] is expected to complete construction by 2021.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/money/business/new-business/2018/05/08/downtown-fifth-des-moines-high-rise-21-c-museum-hotel-mandelbaum/591472002/|title=Des Moines high-rise project adds boutique hotel, art museum|work=Des Moines Register|access-date=2018-09-22|language=en}}</ref> \n\nThe company had been looking to open a hotel in [[Indianapolis]] in the [[Old Indianapolis City Hall|old city hall]], with construction scheduled to begin in 2017, however these plans were scrapped at the end of March 2017 due to problems with financing.<ref>[http://www.indystar.com/story/news/2017/03/27/deal-21c-boutique-hotel-old-city-hall-falls-apart/99699962/ Deal for 21c boutique hotel at old City Hall falls apart], ''Indianapolis Star'', March 27, 2017</ref> 21c Museum Hotels will still be seeking to open a location in the city.\n\n==Restaurants==\nEach 21c location has an onsite restaurant, with many receiving recognition and awards including multiple [[James Beard Foundation Award]] finalists for excellence in cuisine.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nwaonline.com/news/2018/feb/16/bentonville-chef-nominated-for-james-be/|title=Bentonville chef nominated for James Beard award|work=NWADG.com|access-date=2018-05-27|language=en}}</ref>\n\nEach restaurant reflects the local flavor and cuisine of its home city. The current lineup includes:\n\n* The Hive - Bentonville\n* Metropole - Cincinnati\n* Counting House - Durham\n* Lockbox - Lexington\n* Proof on Main - Louisville\n* Gray & Dudley - Nashville\n* Mary Eddy's - Oklahoma City\n* The Savoy - Kansas City\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.21cmuseumhotels.com/}}\n\n[[Category:Hotel chains in the United States]]\n[[Category:Luxury brands]]\n[[Category:2006 establishments in Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Hotels established in 2006]]\n[[Category:Hotels in Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Hotels in Ohio]]\n[[Category:Hotels in Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Louisville, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Art museums established in 2006]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Louisville, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Boutique resort chains]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 2006]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/21c_Museum_Hotels"}
